etymologies: late 18th century (in an earlier sense). Probably partly an alteration of suffix after sub-, and partly from sub- + -fix

definitions: In the writing system of the ancient Maya: an affix positioned below the main sign.

etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in Thomas Baker. Either from classical Latin subfix-, suffix-, past participial stem of subfīgere, suffīgere, or from sub- + fix

definitions: To fix on or attach below or to the end of something else; to append.
(Chiefly in passive). In the writing system of the ancient Maya: to attach as a subfix.
